Basics of Backend:

1. HTTP: Hypertext Transfer Protocol

    a. HTTP is the language used for communication between client and server.

        1. Client = browser / mobile app
        2. Server = backend application

    b. Workflow:

        Client → HTTP Request → Server
        Client ← HTTP Response ← Server

    Example:

       a. You open a website
       b. Browser sends request
       c. Server sends back data

2. HTTP Request (What client sends):

   A request contains:

    1. Method (what you want to do)
    2. URL (where to send)
    3. Headers (extra info)
    4. Body (data, optional)

   Example request:

    POST /login HTTP/1.1
    Host: example.com
    Content-Type: application/json

    {
       "username": "john",
       "password": "1234"
    }

3. HTTP Response (What server sends back):

    Contains:

      1. Status Code
      2. Headers
      3. Body (data)

     Example response:
  
      HTTP/1.1 200 OK
      Content-Type: application/json

      {
        "message": "Login successful"
      }

4. HTTP Methods:

    They define the actions that are required to perform.

     a. GET → Fetch data

         GET /users

        It gets the list of users it doesn't has any body.

     b. POST → Create data

         POST /users
       
        It creates a new user. Also it consists of a body.

     c. PUT → Update data (full update):

         PUT /users/1
 
        It updates the user data with ID = 1.

     d. DELETE → Remove data:

          DELETE /users/1

        It deletes the user data with ID = 1.

     Method	Meaning
     GET	 Read
     POST	 Create
     PUT	 Update
     DELETE	 Delete
     
       This is called CRUD operations

5. HTTPS Status codes:

   a. 200 Series → Success:

        200 OK - Everything worked
        201 Created → New resource created

   b. 400 Series → Client Errors:

	400 Bad Request → Invalid input
	401 Unauthorized → Not logged in
	403 Forbidden → No permission
	404 Not Found → Resource not found

   c. 500 Series → Server Errors

	500 Internal Server Error → Something broke in backend


6. REST API (Representational State Transfer Application Programming Interface):

   REST = a way to design APIs using HTTP properly.

   API (Application Programming Interface): A set of rules and protocols that allows one software application to interact with another. 
